      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems covering beam bending, contact mechanics, and large-displacement nonlinear response verified against analytical solutions or published reference results.",
      "rationale": "Three benchmark problems executed: (1) cantilever beam bending against Euler-Bernoulli solution, error <0.1%; (2) Hertzian contact stress against analytical solution, error <0.5%; (3) nonlinear load-displacement of a pin-jointed frame against published reference, error <0.8%. All within solver tolerance. Numerical code verification satisfied."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrating QoI change <2% between successive refinements; Richardson extrapolation applied to estimate discretization error.",
      "rationale": "Four-level mesh refinement study conducted on the pedicle screw shank and rod interface regions. QoI (peak von Mises stress and construct stiffness) changed by 0.7% between the two finest meshes. Richardson extrapolation estimated discretization error of 0.9% for stiffness and 1.1% for peak stress. Final mesh contains 487,000 elements (C3D8I and C3D6 types). Discretization error within acceptable bounds."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Residual norms monitored; Newton-Raphson convergence achieved at each load increment with force residual <1e-4.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear static analysis performed with automatic load incrementation. Force residual norm converged below 1e-5 at every increment across all 11 simulation runs. No spurious convergence warnings or divergence events recorded. Solver error contribution to QoI uncertainty estimated negligible relative to model-form and input uncertainties."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent peer review of model setup, boundary conditions, and material assignments by a second qualified analyst not involved in original model construction.",
      "rationale": "Independent review conducted by a senior biomechanical engineer (10+ years FEA experience) not involved in model development. Review checklist covered boundary condition application, contact definitions, material property assignments, and load application points. Three minor discrepancies identified and corrected prior to final runs. Use error risk assessed as low following remediation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model form choices documented and justified; sensitivity analysis on key modeling assumptions (contact formulation, material model) performed.",
      "rationale": "Continuum linear-elastic material model for titanium alloy (Ti-6Al-4V) justified by the predominantly elastic response regime of interest (stiffness and yield force QoIs). Frictional contact (μ=0.2) at screw-rod interface validated against published tribological data. Sensitivity analysis showed QoI variation <3% across plausible friction coefficient range 0.15–0.30. Model form uncertainty quantified and incorporated into total uncertainty budget."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from traceable measurements or peer-reviewed literature; geometric inputs from calibrated CMM measurements of test specimens.",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus (114 GPa) and yield strength (880 MPa) for Ti-6Al-4V sourced from ASTM F136 and confirmed by coupon tensile testing of representative material lot (n=5, CV <2%). Geometric dimensions measured by CMM on three representative screws; nominal CAD geometry used with measured deviations <0.05 mm. Input uncertainty propagated via Monte Carlo sampling (n=1000); stiffness QoI 95th-percentile uncertainty contribution 2.3%."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test specimens from production-representative manufacturing lot; dimensional inspection confirms conformance to design drawings.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs drawn from a single production lot (lot number documented). All specimens inspected per ASTM F1717 dimensional requirements; all within specification. Constructs assembled per standardized torque protocol (4 Nm). Two laboratories (Lab A: n=6, Lab B: n=5) used to assess inter-laboratory variability; coefficient of variation for stiffness across all 11 specimens was 3.8%, indicating acceptable manufacturing and assembly consistency."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios; at minimum two distinct load configurations tested to assess model generalizability across the COU envelope.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted exclusively under ASTM F1717 standard compression-bending configuration at a single load angle (0° axial offset per standard). While this configuration is the regulatory standard, it represents only one point in the clinically relevant loading space. Oblique loading conditions (5°–15° off-axis, relevant to scoliosis correction constructs) were not experimentally evaluated. The required level for test conditions is 3 given model risk level 3 and medium decision consequence; the achieved level remains 2 because only a single standardized test condition was employed. This gap is acknowledged; the modeling team assessed the risk as acceptable given that the regulatory submission is scoped exclusively to the F1717 condition and that FEA sensitivity analyses showed <5% QoI sensitivity to ±10° load angle variation. The overall credibility assessment proceeds with this noted shortfall, and the assurance level is judged supportable at Medium given the strength of evidence across the remaining 12 factors.",
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-cou1-test-conditions"
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA input parameters (geometry, material, boundary conditions) demonstrably equivalent to experimental test article parameters; traceability documented.",
      "rationale": "FEA model geometry derived directly from production CAD files used to manufacture test specimens. Material properties matched to lot-specific tensile test data. Boundary conditions (fixed base, actuator displacement applied at superior rod midpoint) replicate ASTM F1717 fixture geometry as confirmed by fixture drawing review. Equivalency of input parameters fully established and documented in the V&V plan."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (E/uval) computed for each QoI; E/uval < 1.96 required for all primary QoIs.",
      "rationale": "E/uval computed per ASME V&V 40 Section 6 for three QoIs: stiffness (1.31), yield force (1.44), force at 40 mm displacement (1.38). All below the 1.96 threshold. Experimental uncertainty uexp estimated from inter-specimen variability; simulation uncertainty usim from combined discretization, input, and model-form contributions. Output comparison criterion satisfied for all three QoIs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs directly linked to the regulatory decision criterion; clinical and biomechanical relevance of each QoI documented.",
      "rationale": "Three QoIs selected: construct stiffness (linked to load-sharing and adjacent segment effects), yield force (structural integrity threshold), and force at 40 mm displacement (ASTM F1717 regulatory endpoint). All three are directly referenced in FDA guidance for spinal implant 510(k) submissions and in ASTM F1717. QoI relevance to COU fully established."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
